subSection.paragraph:
Terpenes constitute the largest group of secondary metabolites exhibiting diverse functions in life. Structurally, they are classified based on the number and organizational pattern of their carbon atoms. Diterpenes are biosynthesized from geranyl geranyl pyrophosphate (GGPP) as a precursor which is obtained by the head/tail attachment of isopentenyldiphosphate (C5) to farnesyldiphosphate (C15) (
Breitmaier, 2006
). Biogenetically, diterpenes are classified as acyclic (phytanes), bicyclic (labdanes, halimane, clerodanes), tricyclic (pimaranes, abietanes, cassanes, rosanes, vouacapanes, podocarpanes), tetracyclic (trachlobanes, kauranes, aphidicolanes, stemodanes, stemaranes, bayeranes, atisanes, gibberellanes) and macrocyclic diterpenes (taxanes, cembranes, daphnanes, tiglianes, ingenanes) (
Bruneton, 1995
; 
Charlwood and Banthorpe, 1991
; 
Hanson, 2004
, 
2009
; 
Roberts, 2007
).

Moreover, cembranes are the largest and most structurally diversified group of diterpenes isolated from terrestrial plants, marine organisms and insects (
Yang et al., 2012
).

Following the isolation of the first cembrane from the resin of the pine tree (
Dauben et al., 1965
), hundreds of cembranes have been reported from the three aforementioned sources (
Weinheimer et al., 1979
; 
Yang et al., 2012
).

From a structural point of view, cembranes are 14-membered macrocyclic ring, early-class diterpenoids. Their occurrence encompasses terrestrial plants (resinous plants like frankincense and tobacco trees), marine invertebrates (soft corals and sponges) and insects (
Yang et al., 2012
).

In recent years, cembranoids have attracted increasing interest due to their wide range of biological activities including but limited to anti-inflammatory, anticancer, ichthyo-toxic, anti-human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and antimicrobial activities (
Liang et al., 2013
; 
Xi et al., 2013
; 
Yang et al., 2012
). Incensole (1) and incensole acetate (2) were found in an ointment formulation Bpap (AS-050509- E2h) made by AureliaSan GmbH, Bisingen (
Germany
) when analyzed by Paul (2012).

Our two research groups were involved on drugs discovery from frankincense in particular boswellic acids and incensole derivatives. We have recently performed structural (
Avula et al., 2016
) and analytical (
Al-Shidhani et al., 2018
) studies on incensole and its acetate. Moreover, our current studies focus on understanding the GABAergic mechanism in the effectiveness of natural and synthetically modified incensole derivatives in neuro-pharmacological disorders which should provide new insights on the mechanism of action of these two interesting molecules.

Six analyses were reported for 

Boswellia serrata

(
Table 2
) using different methods of extraction and analysis and all showed the absence of incensole and incensole acetate (
Al-Shidhani et al., 2018
; 
Camarda et al., 2007
; 
Hamm et al., 2005
; 
Niebler and Buettner, 2016
) except one (Paul, 2012), which reported 
1.4 g
/g in % for incensole.

The activity profile of incensole acetate (2), has been evaluated by behavioral, pharmacological, and physiological assays. Moussaieff et al. have evaluated the psychoactive properties of incensole acetate (2) by activating TRPV3 channels in the brain (
Moussaieff et al., 2008a
). TRPV3 (Transient receptor potential vanilloid) is an ion channel associated in the perception of warmth in the skin (
Chung et al., 2004
; 
Ramsey et al., 2006
). The role of TRPV3 channels is unknown yet but TRPV3 mRNA has also been found in neurons all over the brain (
Smith et al., 2002
; 
Xu et al., 2002
).

Moussaieff et al. have found the incensole acetate (2) to be a potent TRPV3 agonist that causes anxiolytic-like and antidepressive-like behavioral effects in wild-type (WT) mice with associated changes in c-Fos activation in the brain. In TRPV3/mice, these behavioral effects were not noted so it was recommended they are mediated via TRPV3 channels (
Moussaieff et al., 2008a
).

The activity of incensole acetate (2) on TRPV3 channels was more specific than that of 2-aminoethoxydiphenyl borate due to its weak effect on TRPV1, TRPV2, or TRPV4. Moreover, the anxiolytic and antidepressant effects of the TRPV3 channels are associated with the activity in animal models. This finding is in agreement with the fact that brain TRPV3 channels should be targeted in order to treat depressive and anxiety disorders (
Moussaieff et al., 2008a
).

The incensole acetate (2) was found to be the only selective TRPV3 agonist so far, therefore to explore the chemical space around incensole acetate (2), Pollastro et al., (2016) have synthesized 12 different derivatives of 2 and developed a complete structure activity relationship for TRPV3 (
Pollastro et al., 2016
). Incensole (1) and serratol (G) in addition to a series of semisynthetic derivatives of incensole were screened for transient receptor potential vanilloid 3 (TRPV3); the putative molecular targets agree with the observed psychotropic effect of incensole acetate (2) (
Pollastro et al., 2016
).

The nonanoate (3) and the phenylacetate ester (5) derivatives of incensole (1) showed a potent inhibitory activity on NF-κB activation with IC 
50
values of 35.5 ± 1.1 and 22.4 ± 2.4 μM, respectively. Furthermore, incensole nonanoate (3) (
Scheme 3
) also inhibited STAT3 (IC 
50
= 38.7 ± 3.99 μM), while all the other analogs were inactive. Interestingly these inhibitors (incensole derivatives) of NF-κB are devoid from other NF-κB inhibitors as they lack electrophilicity and redox properties (
Moussaieff et al., 2007
). Pollastro and coworkers (
Pollastro et al., 2016
) suggested that incensole derivatives are good for the inhibition of transcriptions factors (NF-κB and STAT3) as both are involved in inflammation. For example, incensole (1) and its nonanoate ester (3) could inhibit the activity of both NF-κB and STAT3 (
Pollastro et al., 2016
).
